@ThinkingandTinkering Sure, not everyone lives somewhere where there are skips full of great stuff on every street corner, but there's always the local tip.  Over here you're not allowed to recover stuff from the tip, but chatting with the bloke generally means you can, and a bottle of wine every now and then means you're a valued client who can place orders :). Then there's farcebook marketplace and equivalents.  I don't book my face, but just looked, there's a bloke 5km away selling 5 jigsaws, 5 sanders, 2 drills and 3 circular saws, all "for pieces", 30 euros the lot.  In france we also have "leboncoin", kinda a french craigslist, at the moment there's 23 offers of busted tools under 15 euros each all within our 10km lockdown limit.  I know who's selling two of them, I work with him, he's even more of a valued client at the tip than I am :)

Don't get me wrong, I'm very much not against buying stuff new, even cheap stuff, and if there was some cheap gearbox that existed without requiring major adaptation, I'd be all for it, but what you're suggesting here makes little sense.  Those winches are intended for very low rotational speed, short periods of use (rolling in, say, 3 or 4 metres of rope), occasional use (maybe twice a day), with little concern for losses, and they just barely manage to handle that.  We would get maybe 120 days out of them, using them once a day (one roll out in the morning, one winch in in the evening) before they fall apart totally and need repair.  We were using them on (they are, in fact supplied equipment for) "télécorde" installations - rope drags for beginners in ski resorts - to lift the rope out of the way overnight so the grooming machines can get underneath.

For the same money, buy a busted angle grinder, reuse a high performance power transmission element already running on bearings, scrounge a couple of big coils from the stator, a decent shaft from the rotor, a switch, a plug on a cable, maybe a small variac, and there's probably usable bits in the rotor as well.  Would you like to guess what I was replacing those crappy winches with after they failed?  Or you could try and find an old sturmey-archer equipped bicycle and strip the rear hub from it.  People give those away for free (see, once again, faceache).
